latestPosts.caption:
“Violence against women is not a private matter; it is a public crisis.” — Hillary Clinton
The handprint on her face is a brutal reminder of the violence inflicted upon her. Yet, this mark does not carry shame, only strength. It stands as proof that the trauma did not break her, but shaped her into a force that refuses to remain hidden or quiet.

latestPosts.caption:
“I am not free while any woman is unfree, even when her shackles are different from my own.’ — Audre Lorde, Sister Outsider.”
Her silence was the reflection of a world that demanded her submission. Yet in every restriction, she fought for the right to speak, to exist fully, and to define herself. Her voice, once silenced, became the anthem of her liberation, a call for freedom that would not be ignored.

latestPosts.caption:
“She came as the dawn—dragging light into places that feared it.”
They painted her too much. Too loud. Too fierce.
She became everything they weren’t ready for.
Wearing heartbreak like haute couture,
and walking bold into every hush.

latestPosts.caption:
The marks on their skin are not just ink—they are stories, wounds, and defiance written in protest.”
In the faces of these individuals, the markings are more than symbols—they are messages of resistance. Each stroke, each word written is a testament to the struggles faced, a collective call to break free from silence and challenge the societal norms that seek to oppress.

latestPosts.caption:
“She doesn’t need fixing—she’s just learning how to hold her own.”
Every glance thrown her way, a reminder of the fragile mask they put on her.
But underneath, there’s strength, and it’s more than delicate.
It’s the silence of a storm that refuses to be anything but itself.
